<s> Near the end of the 19th century compound engines came into widespread use . <\s>
<s> Compound engines exhausted steam in to successively larger cylinders to accommodate the higher volumes at reduced pressures , giving improved efficiency . <\s>
<s> These stages were called expansions , with double and triple expansion engines being common , especially in shipping where efficiency was important to reduce the weight of coal carried . <\s>
<s> Steam engines remained the dominant source of power until the early 20th century , when advances in the design of electric motors and internal combustion engines gradually resulted in the replacement of reciprocating steam engines , with shipping in the 20th-century relying upon the steam turbine . <\s>
<s> The final major evolution of the steam engine design was the use of steam turbines starting in the late part of the 19th century . <\s>
<s> Steam turbines are generally more efficient than reciprocating piston type steam engines , have fewer moving parts , and provide rotary power directly instead of through a connecting rod system or similar means . <\s>
<s> Steam turbines virtually replaced reciprocating engines in electricity generating stations early in the 20th century , where their efficiency , higher speed appropriate to generator service , and smooth rotation were advantages . <\s>
