<s> A method to lessen the magnitude of this heating and cooling was invented in 1804 by British engineer Arthur Woolf , who patented his Woolf high-pressure compound engine in 1805 . <\s>
<s> In the compound engine , high-pressure steam from the boiler expands in a high-pressure cylinder and then enters one or more subsequent lower-pressure cylinders . <\s>
<s> The complete expansion of the steam now occurs across multiple cylinders and as less expansion now occurs in each cylinder less heat is lost by the steam in each . <\s>
<s> This reduces the magnitude of cylinder heating and cooling , increasing the efficiency of the engine . <\s>
<s> By staging the expansion in multiple cylinders , torque variability can be reduced . <\s>
<s> To derive equal work from lower-pressure steam requires a larger cylinder volume as this steam occupies a greater volume . <\s>
<s> Therefore , the bore , and often the stroke , are increased in low-pressure cylinders resulting in larger cylinders . <\s>
<s> The main use for steam turbines is in electricity generation however the recent widespread application of large gas turbine units and typical combined cycle power plants has resulted in reduction of this percentage to the 80 % regime for steam turbines . <\s>
<s> In electricity production , the high speed of turbine rotation matches well with the speed of modern electric generators , which are typically direct connected to their driving turbines . <\s>
<s> In marine service , , steam turbines with reduction gearing dominated large ship propulsion throughout the late 20th century , being more efficient than reciprocating steam engines . <\s>
<s> In recent decades , reciprocating Diesel engines , and gas turbines , have almost entirely supplanted steam propulsion for marine applications . <\s>
<s> The Rankine cycle is the fundamental thermodynamic underpinning of the steam engine . <\s>
<s> The cycle is an arrangement of components as is typically used for simple power production , and utilizes the phase change of water to provide a practical heat/power conversion system . <\s>
<s> The heat is supplied externally to a closed loop with some of the heat added being converted to work and the waste heat being removed in a condenser . <\s>
<s> The Rankine cycle is used in virtually all steam power production applications . <\s>
<s> In the 1990s , Rankine steam cycles generated about 90 % of all electric power used throughout the world , including virtually all solar , biomass , coal and nuclear power plants . <\s>
<s> It is named after William John Macquorn Rankine , a Scottish polymath . <\s>
<s> The historical measure of a steam engine 's energy efficiency was its `` duty '' . <\s>
<s> The concept of duty was first introduced by Watt in order to illustrate how much more efficient his engines were over the earlier Newcomen designs . <\s>
<s> Duty is the number of foot-pounds of work delivered by burning one bushel of coal . <\s>
<s> The best examples of Newcomen designs had a duty of about 7 million , but most were closer to 5 million . <\s>
<s> Watt 's original low-pressure designs were able to deliver duty as high as 25 million , but averaged about 17 . <\s>
<s> This was a three-fold improvement over the average Newcomen design . <\s>
<s> Early Watt engines equipped with high-pressure steam improved this to 65 million . <\s>
<s> Reciprocating piston type steam engines remained the dominant source of power until the early 20th century , when advances in the design of electric motors and internal combustion engines gradually resulted in the replacement of reciprocating steam engines in commercial usage , and the ascendancy of steam turbines in power generation . <\s>
<s> Considering that the great majority of worldwide electric generation is produced by turbine type steam engines , the `` steam age '' is continuing with energy levels far beyond those of the turn of the 19th century . <\s>
<s> The first commercial steam-powered device was a water pump , developed in 1698 by Thomas Savery . <\s>
<s> It used condensing steam to create a vacuum which was used to raise water from below , then it used steam pressure to raise it higher . <\s>
<s> Small engines were effective though larger models were problematic . <\s>
<s> They proved only to have a limited lift height and were prone to boiler explosions . <\s>
<s> It received some use in mines , pumping stations and for supplying water wheels used to power textile machinery . <\s>
<s> An attractive feature of the Savery engine was its low cost . <\s>
<s> Bento de Moura Portugal introduced an ingenious improvement of Savery 's construction `` to render it capable of working itself '' , as described by John Smeaton in the Philosophical Transactions published in 1751 . <\s>
<s> It continued to be manufactured until the late 18th century . <\s>
<s> One engine was still known to be operating in 1820 . <\s>
<s> Around 1800 Richard Trevithick and , separately , Oliver Evans in 1801 introduced engines using high-pressure steam ; Trevithick obtained his high-pressure engine patent in 1802 . <\s>
<s> These were much more powerful for a given cylinder size than previous engines and could be made small enough for transport applications . <\s>
<s> Thereafter , technological developments and improvements in manufacturing techniques resulted in the design of more efficient engines that could be smaller , faster , or more powerful , depending on the intended application . <\s>
<s> Although the reciprocating steam engine is no longer in widespread commercial use , various companies are exploring or exploiting the potential of the engine as an alternative to internal combustion engines . <\s>
<s> The company Energiprojekt AB in Sweden has made progress in using modern materials for harnessing the power of steam . <\s>
<s> The efficiency of Energiprojekt 's steam engine reaches some 27-30 % on high-pressure engines . <\s>
<s> It is a single-step , 5-cylinder engine with superheated steam and consumes approx. 4 kg of steam per kWh . <\s>
<s> Where CHP is not used , steam turbines in power stations use surface condensers as a cold sink . <\s>
<s> The condensers are cooled by water flow from oceans , rivers , lakes , and often by cooling towers which evaporate water to provide cooling energy removal . <\s>
<s> The resulting condensed hot water output from the condenser is then put back into the boiler via a pump . <\s>
<s> A dry type cooling tower is similar to an automobile radiator and is used in locations where water is costly . <\s>
<s> Evaporative cooling towers use the rejected heat to evaporate water ; this water is kept separate from the condensate , which circulates in a closed system and returns to the boiler . <\s>
<s> Such towers often have visible plumes due to the evaporated water condensing into droplets carried up by the warm air . <\s>
<s> Evaporative cooling towers need less water flow than `` once-through '' cooling by river or lake water ; a 700 megawatt coal-fired power plant may use about 3600 cubic metres of make-up water every hour for evaporative cooling , but would need about twenty times as much if cooled by river water . <\s>
<s> The centrifugal governor was adopted by James Watt for use on a steam engine in 1788 after Watt 's partner Boulton saw one at a flour mill Boulton & Watt were building . <\s>
<s> The governor could not actually hold a set speed , because it would assume a new constant speed in response to load changes . <\s>
<s> The governor was able to handle smaller variations such as those caused by fluctuating heat load to the boiler . <\s>
<s> Also , there was a tendency for oscillation whenever there was a speed change . <\s>
<s> As a consequence , engines equipped only with this governor were not suitable for operations requiring constant speed , such as cotton spinning . <\s>
<s> The governor was improved over time and coupled with variable steam cut off , good speed control in response to changes in load was attainable near the end of the 19th century . <\s>
<s> The adoption of compounding was common for industrial units , for road engines and almost universal for marine engines after 1880 ; it was not universally popular in railway locomotives where it was often perceived as complicated . <\s>
<s> This is partly due to the harsh railway operating environment and limited space afforded by the loading gauge . <\s>
<s> However , although never in the majority , it was popular in many other countries . <\s>
<s> The simplest valve gears give events of fixed length during the engine cycle and often make the engine rotate in only one direction . <\s>
<s> Most however have a reversing mechanism which additionally can provide means for saving steam as speed and momentum are gained by gradually `` shortening the cutoff '' or rather , shortening the admission event ; this in turn proportionately lengthens the expansion period . <\s>
<s> However , as one and the same valve usually controls both steam flows , a short cutoff at admission adversely affects the exhaust and compression periods which should ideally always be kept fairly constant ; if the exhaust event is too brief , the totality of the exhaust steam can not evacuate the cylinder , choking it and giving excessive compression . <\s>
<s> Using boiling water to produce mechanical motion goes back over 2000 years , but early devices were not practical . <\s>
<s> The Spanish inventor Jerónimo de Ayanz y Beaumont obtained the first patent for a steam engine in 1606 . <\s>
<s> In 1698 Thomas Savery patented a steam pump that used steam in direct contact with the water being pumped . <\s>
<s> Savery 's steam pump used condensing steam to create a vacuum and draw water into a chamber , and then applied pressurized steam to further pump the water . <\s>
<s> Thomas Newcomen 's atmospheric engine was the first commercial true steam engine using a piston , and was used in 1712 for pumping in a mine . <\s>
<s> A steam turbine consists of one or more rotors mounted on a drive shaft , alternating with a series of stators fixed to the turbine casing . <\s>
<s> The rotors have a propeller-like arrangement of blades at the outer edge . <\s>
<s> Steam acts upon these blades , producing rotary motion . <\s>
<s> The stator consists of a similar , but fixed , series of blades that serve to redirect the steam flow onto the next rotor stage . <\s>
<s> A steam turbine often exhausts into a surface condenser that provides a vacuum . <\s>
<s> The stages of a steam turbine are typically arranged to extract the maximum potential work from a specific velocity and pressure of steam , giving rise to a series of variably sized high- and low-pressure stages . <\s>
<s> Turbines are only efficient if they rotate at relatively high speed , therefore they are usually connected to reduction gearing to drive lower speed applications , such as a ship 's propeller . <\s>
<s> In the vast majority of large electric generating stations , turbines are directly connected to generators with no reduction gearing . <\s>
<s> Typical speeds are 3600 revolutions per minute in the USA with 60 Hertz power , 3000 RPM in Europe and other countries with 50 Hertz electric power systems . <\s>
<s> In nuclear power applications the turbines typically run at half these speeds , 1800 RPM and 1500 RPM . <\s>
<s> A turbine rotor is also only capable of providing power when rotating in one direction . <\s>
<s> Therefore , a reversing stage or gearbox is usually required where power is required in the opposite direction . <\s>
<s> The weight of boilers and condensers generally makes the power-to-weight ratio of a steam plant lower than for internal combustion engines . <\s>
<s> For mobile applications steam has been largely superseded by internal combustion engines or electric motors . <\s>
<s> However , most electric power is generated using steam turbine plant , so that indirectly the world 's industry is still dependent on steam power . <\s>
<s> Recent concerns about fuel sources and pollution have incited a renewed interest in steam both as a component of cogeneration processes and as a prime mover . <\s>
<s> This is becoming known as the Advanced Steam movement . <\s>
<s> It is possible to use a mechanism based on a pistonless rotary engine such as the Wankel engine in place of the cylinders and valve gear of a conventional reciprocating steam engine . <\s>
<s> Many such engines have been designed , from the time of James Watt to the present day , but relatively few were actually built and even fewer went into quantity production ; see link at bottom of article for more details . <\s>
<s> The major problem is the difficulty of sealing the rotors to make them steam-tight in the face of wear and thermal expansion ; the resulting leakage made them very inefficient . <\s>
<s> Lack of expansive working , or any means of control of the cutoff is also a serious problem with many such designs . <\s>
<s> The next major step occurred when James Watt developed an improved version of Newcomen 's engine , with a separate condenser . <\s>
<s> Boulton and Watt 's early engines used half as much coal as John Smeaton 's improved version of Newcomen 's . <\s>
<s> Newcomen 's and Watt 's early engines were `` atmospheric '' . <\s>
<s> They were powered by air pressure pushing a piston into the partial vacuum generated by condensing steam , instead of the pressure of expanding steam . <\s>
<s> The engine cylinders had to be large because the only usable force acting on them was due to atmospheric pressure . <\s>
<s> Steam engines frequently possess two independent mechanisms for ensuring that the pressure in the boiler does not go too high ; one may be adjusted by the user , the second is typically designed as an ultimate fail-safe . <\s>
<s> Such safety valves traditionally used a simple lever to restrain a plug valve in the top of a boiler . <\s>
<s> One end of the lever carried a weight or spring that restrained the valve against steam pressure . <\s>
<s> Early valves could be adjusted by engine drivers , leading to many accidents when a driver fastened the valve down to allow greater steam pressure and more power from the engine . <\s>
<s> The more recent type of safety valve uses an adjustable spring-loaded valve , which is locked such that operators may not tamper with its adjustment unless a seal illegally is broken . <\s>
<s> This arrangement is considerably safer . <\s>
<s> The acme of the horizontal engine was the Corliss steam engine , patented in 1849 , which was a four-valve counter flow engine with separate steam admission and exhaust valves and automatic variable steam cutoff . <\s>
<s> When Corliss was given the Rumford medal the committee said that `` no one invention since Watt 's time has so enhanced the efficiency of the steam engine '' . <\s>
<s> In addition to using 30 % less steam , it provided more uniform speed due to variable steam cut off , making it well suited to manufacturing , especially cotton spinning . <\s>
<s> The steam engine contributed much to the development of thermodynamic theory ; however , the only applications of scientific theory that influenced the steam engine were the original concepts of harnessing the power of steam and atmospheric pressure and knowledge of properties of heat and steam . <\s>
<s> The experimental measurements made by Watt on a model steam engine led to the development of the separate condenser . <\s>
<s> Watt independently discovered latent heat , which was confirmed by the original discoverer Joseph Black , who also advised Watt on experimental procedures . <\s>
<s> Watt was also aware of the change in the boiling point of water with pressure . <\s>
<s> Otherwise , the improvements to the engine itself were more mechanical in nature . <\s>
<s> The thermodynamic concepts of the Rankine cycle did give engineers the understanding needed to calculate efficiency which aided the development of modern high-pressure and -temperature boilers and the steam turbine . <\s>
<s> One of the principal advantages the Rankine cycle holds over others is that during the compression stage relatively little work is required to drive the pump , the working fluid being in its liquid phase at this point . <\s>
<s> By condensing the fluid , the work required by the pump consumes only 1 % to 3 % of the turbine power and contributes to a much higher efficiency for a real cycle . <\s>
<s> The benefit of this is lost somewhat due to the lower heat addition temperature . <\s>
<s> Gas turbines , for instance , have turbine entry temperatures approaching 1500 °C . <\s>
<s> Nonetheless , the efficiencies of actual large steam cycles and large modern gas turbines are fairly well matched . <\s>
<s> Other components are often present ; pumps to supply water to the boiler during operation , condensers to recirculate the water and recover the latent heat of vaporisation , and superheaters to raise the temperature of the steam above its saturated vapour point , and various mechanisms to increase the draft for fireboxes . <\s>
<s> When coal is used , a chain or screw stoking mechanism and its drive engine or motor may be included to move the fuel from a supply bin to the firebox . <\s>
<s> Land-based steam engines could exhaust much of their steam , as feed water was usually readily available . <\s>
<s> Prior to and during World War I , the expansion engine dominated marine applications where high vessel speed was not essential . <\s>
<s> It was however superseded by the British invention steam turbine where speed was required , for instance in warships , such as the dreadnought battleships , and ocean liners . <\s>
<s> HMS Dreadnought of 1905 was the first major warship to replace the proven technology of the reciprocating engine with the then-novel steam turbine . <\s>
<s> Virtually all nuclear power plants generate electricity by heating water to provide steam that drives a turbine connected to an electrical generator . <\s>
<s> Nuclear-powered ships and submarines either use a steam turbine directly for main propulsion , with generators providing auxiliary power , or else employ turbo-electric transmission , where the steam drives a turbo generator set with propulsion provided by electric motors . <\s>
<s> A limited number of steam turbine railroad locomotives were manufactured . <\s>
<s> Some non-condensing direct-drive locomotives did meet with some success for long haul freight operations in Sweden and for express passenger work in Britain , but were not repeated . <\s>
<s> Elsewhere , notably in the U.S.A. , more advanced designs with electric transmission were built experimentally , but not reproduced . <\s>
<s> It was found that steam turbines were not ideally suited to the railroad environment and these locomotives failed to oust the classic reciprocating steam unit in the way that modern diesel and electric traction has done . <\s>
<s> The Rankine cycle is sometimes referred to as a practical Carnot cycle because , when an efficient turbine is used , the TS diagram begins to resemble the Carnot cycle . <\s>
<s> The main difference is that heat addition and rejection are isobaric processes in the Rankine cycle and isothermal processes in the theoretical Carnot cycle . <\s>
<s> In this cycle a pump is used to pressurize the working fluid which is received from the condenser as a liquid not as a gas . <\s>
<s> Pumping the working fluid in liquid form during the cycle requires a small fraction of the energy to transport it compared to the energy needed to compress the working fluid in gaseous form in a compressor . <\s>
<s> The cycle of a reciprocating steam engine differs from that of turbines because of condensation and re-evaporation occurring in the cylinder or in the steam inlet passages . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is a chemical element with symbol O and atomic number 8 . <\s>
<s> It is a member of the chalcogen group on the periodic table and is a highly reactive nonmetal and oxidizing agent that readily forms compounds with most elements . <\s>
<s> By mass , oxygen is the third-most abundant element in the universe , after hydrogen and helium . <\s>
<s> At standard temperature and pressure , two atoms of the element bind to form dioxygen , a colorless and odorless diatomic gas with the formula O2 . <\s>
<s> Diatomic oxygen gas constitutes 20.8 % of the Earth 's atmosphere . <\s>
<s> However , monitoring of atmospheric oxygen levels show a global downward trend , because of fossil-fuel burning . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is the most abundant element by mass in the Earth 's crust as part of oxide compounds such as silicon dioxide , making up almost half of the crust 's mass . <\s>
<s> Many major classes of organic molecules in living organisms , such as proteins , nucleic acids , carbohydrates , and fats , contain oxygen , as do the major inorganic compounds that are constituents of animal shells , teeth , and bone . <\s>
<s> Most of the mass of living organisms is oxygen as it is a part of water , the major constituent of lifeforms . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is used in cellular respiration and released by photosynthesis , which uses the energy of sunlight to produce oxygen from water . <\s>
<s> It is too chemically reactive to remain a free element in air without being continuously replenished by the photosynthetic action of living organisms . <\s>
<s> Another form of oxygen , ozone , strongly absorbs UVB radiation and consequently the high-altitude ozone layer helps protect the biosphere from ultraviolet radiation , but is a pollutant near the surface where it is a by-product of smog . <\s>
<s> At even higher low earth orbit altitudes , sufficient atomic oxygen is present to cause erosion for spacecraft . <\s>
<s> In the late 17th century , Robert Boyle proved that air is necessary for combustion . <\s>
<s> English chemist John Mayow refined this work by showing that fire requires only a part of air that he called spiritus nitroaereus or just nitroaereus . <\s>
<s> In one experiment he found that placing either a mouse or a lit candle in a closed container over water caused the water to rise and replace one-fourteenth of the air 's volume before extinguishing the subjects . <\s>
<s> From this he surmised that nitroaereus is consumed in both respiration and combustion . <\s>
<s> In the meantime , on August 1 , 1774 , an experiment conducted by the British clergyman Joseph Priestley focused sunlight on mercuric oxide inside a glass tube , which liberated a gas he named `` dephlogisticated air '' . <\s>
<s> He noted that candles burned brighter in the gas and that a mouse was more active and lived longer while breathing it . <\s>
<s> After breathing the gas himself , he wrote : `` The feeling of it to my lungs was not sensibly different from that of common air , but I fancied that my breast felt peculiarly light and easy for some time afterwards . '' <\s>
<s> Priestley published his findings in 1775 in a paper titled `` An Account of Further Discoveries in Air '' which was included in the second volume of his book titled Experiments and Observations on Different Kinds of Air . <\s>
<s> Because he published his findings first , Priestley is usually given priority in the discovery . <\s>
<s> One of the first known experiments on the relationship between combustion and air was conducted by the 2nd century BCE Greek writer on mechanics , Philo of Byzantium . <\s>
<s> In his work Pneumatica , Philo observed that inverting a vessel over a burning candle and surrounding the vessel 's neck with water resulted in some water rising into the neck . <\s>
<s> Philo incorrectly surmised that parts of the air in the vessel were converted into the classical element fire and thus were able to escape through pores in the glass . <\s>
<s> Many centuries later Leonardo da Vinci built on Philo 's work by observing that a portion of air is consumed during combustion and respiration . <\s>
<s> Highly concentrated sources of oxygen promote rapid combustion . <\s>
<s> Fire and explosion hazards exist when concentrated oxidants and fuels are brought into close proximity ; an ignition event , such as heat or a spark , is needed to trigger combustion . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is the oxidant , not the fuel , but nevertheless the source of most of the chemical energy released in combustion . <\s>
<s> Combustion hazards also apply to compounds of oxygen with a high oxidative potential , such as peroxides , chlorates , nitrates , perchlorates , and dichromates because they can donate oxygen to a fire . <\s>
<s> Concentrated O2 will allow combustion to proceed rapidly and energetically . <\s>
<s> Steel pipes and storage vessels used to store and transmit both gaseous and liquid oxygen will act as a fuel ; and therefore the design and manufacture of O2 systems requires special training to ensure that ignition sources are minimized . <\s>
<s> The fire that killed the Apollo 1 crew in a launch pad test spread so rapidly because the capsule was pressurized with pure O2 but at slightly more than atmospheric pressure , instead of the 1⁄3 normal pressure that would be used in a mission . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is present in the atmosphere in trace quantities in the form of carbon dioxide . <\s>
<s> The Earth 's crustal rock is composed in large part of oxides of silicon , aluminium , iron , and calcium carbonate . <\s>
<s> The rest of the Earth 's crust is also made of oxygen compounds , in particular various complex silicates . <\s>
<s> The Earth 's mantle , of much larger mass than the crust , is largely composed of silicates of magnesium and iron . <\s>
<s> John Dalton 's original atomic hypothesis assumed that all elements were monatomic and that the atoms in compounds would normally have the simplest atomic ratios with respect to one another . <\s>
<s> For example , Dalton assumed that water 's formula was HO , giving the atomic mass of oxygen as 8 times that of hydrogen , instead of the modern value of about 16 . <\s>
<s> In 1805 , Joseph Louis Gay-Lussac and Alexander von Humboldt showed that water is formed of two volumes of hydrogen and one volume of oxygen ; and by 1811 Amedeo Avogadro had arrived at the correct interpretation of water 's composition , based on what is now called Avogadro 's law and the assumption of diatomic elemental molecules . <\s>
<s> Highly combustible materials that leave little residue , such as wood or coal , were thought to be made mostly of phlogiston ; whereas non-combustible substances that corrode , such as iron , contained very little . <\s>
<s> Air did not play a role in phlogiston theory , nor were any initial quantitative experiments conducted to test the idea ; instead , it was based on observations of what happens when something burns , that most common objects appear to become lighter and seem to lose something in the process . <\s>
<s> The fact that a substance like wood gains overall weight in burning was hidden by the buoyancy of the gaseous combustion products . <\s>
<s> Indeed , one of the first clues that the phlogiston theory was incorrect was that metals , too , gain weight in rusting . <\s>
<s> In this dioxygen , the two oxygen atoms are chemically bonded to each other . <\s>
<s> The bond can be variously described based on level of theory , but is reasonably and simply described as a covalent double bond that results from the filling of molecular orbitals formed from the atomic orbitals of the individual oxygen atoms , the filling of which results in a bond order of two . <\s>
<s> More specifically , the double bond is the result of sequential , low-to-high energy , or Aufbau , filling of orbitals , and the resulting cancellation of contributions from the 2s electrons , after sequential filling of the low σ and σ * orbitals ; σ overlap of the two atomic 2p orbitals that lie along the O-O molecular axis and π overlap of two pairs of atomic 2p orbitals perpendicular to the O-O molecular axis , and then cancellation of contributions from the remaining two of the six 2p electrons after their partial filling of the lowest π and π * orbitals . <\s>
<s> Oxygen was discovered independently by Carl Wilhelm Scheele , in Uppsala , in 1773 or earlier , and Joseph Priestley in Wiltshire , in 1774 , but Priestley is often given priority because his work was published first . <\s>
<s> The name oxygen was coined in 1777 by Antoine Lavoisier , whose experiments with oxygen helped to discredit the then-popular phlogiston theory of combustion and corrosion . <\s>
<s> Its name derives from the Greek roots ὀξύς oxys , `` acid '' , literally `` sharp '' , referring to the sour taste of acids and -γενής -genes , `` producer '' , literally `` begetter '' , because at the time of naming , it was mistakenly thought that all acids required oxygen in their composition . <\s>
<s> Common uses of oxygen includes the production cycle of steel , plastics and textiles , brazing , welding and cutting of steels and other metals , rocket propellant , in oxygen therapy and life support systems in aircraft , submarines , spaceflight and diving . <\s>
<s> This combination of cancellations and σ and π overlaps results in dioxygen 's double bond character and reactivity , and a triplet electronic ground state . <\s>
<s> An electron configuration with two unpaired electrons as found in dioxygen , orbitals that are of equal energy — i.e. , degenerate — is a configuration termed a spin triplet state . <\s>
<s> Hence , the ground state of the O2 molecule is referred to as triplet oxygen . <\s>
<s> The highest energy , partially filled orbitals are antibonding , and so their filling weakens the bond order from three to two . <\s>
<s> Because of its unpaired electrons , triplet oxygen reacts only slowly with most organic molecules , which have paired electron spins ; this prevents spontaneous combustion . <\s>
<s> In one experiment , Lavoisier observed that there was no overall increase in weight when tin and air were heated in a closed container . <\s>
<s> He noted that air rushed in when he opened the container , which indicated that part of the trapped air had been consumed . <\s>
<s> He also noted that the tin had increased in weight and that increase was the same as the weight of the air that rushed back in . <\s>
<s> This and other experiments on combustion were documented in his book Sur la combustion en général , which was published in 1777 . <\s>
<s> In that work , he proved that air is a mixture of two gases ; ' vital air ' , which is essential to combustion and respiration , and azote , which did not support either . <\s>
<s> Azote later became nitrogen in English , although it has kept the name in French and several other European languages . <\s>
<s> Trioxygen is usually known as ozone and is a very reactive allotrope of oxygen that is damaging to lung tissue . <\s>
<s> Ozone is produced in the upper atmosphere when O2 combines with atomic oxygen made by the splitting of O2 by ultraviolet radiation . <\s>
<s> Since ozone absorbs strongly in the UV region of the spectrum , the ozone layer of the upper atmosphere functions as a protective radiation shield for the planet . <\s>
<s> Near the Earth 's surface , it is a pollutant formed as a by-product of automobile exhaust . <\s>
<s> The metastable molecule tetraoxygen was discovered in 2001 , and was assumed to exist in one of the six phases of solid oxygen . <\s>
<s> It was proven in 2006 that this phase , created by pressurizing O2 to 20 GPa , is in fact a rhombohedral O8 cluster . <\s>
<s> This cluster has the potential to be a much more powerful oxidizer than either O2 or O3 and may therefore be used in rocket fuel . <\s>
<s> A metallic phase was discovered in 1990 when solid oxygen is subjected to a pressure of above 96 GPa and it was shown in 1998 that at very low temperatures , this phase becomes superconducting . <\s>
<s> The common allotrope of elemental oxygen on Earth is called dioxygen , O2 . <\s>
<s> It is the form that is a major part of the Earth 's atmosphere . <\s>
<s> O2 has a bond length of 121 pm and a bond energy of 498 kJ·mol−1 , which is smaller than the energy of other double bonds or pairs of single bonds in the biosphere and responsible for the exothermic reaction of O2 with any organic molecule . <\s>
<s> Due to its energy content , O2 is used by complex forms of life , such as animals , in cellular respiration . <\s>
<s> Other aspects of O2 are covered in the remainder of this article . <\s>
<s> In 1891 Scottish chemist James Dewar was able to produce enough liquid oxygen to study . <\s>
<s> The first commercially viable process for producing liquid oxygen was independently developed in 1895 by German engineer Carl von Linde and British engineer William Hampson . <\s>
<s> Both men lowered the temperature of air until it liquefied and then distilled the component gases by boiling them off one at a time and capturing them . <\s>
<s> Later , in 1901 , oxyacetylene welding was demonstrated for the first time by burning a mixture of acetylene and compressed O2 . <\s>
<s> This method of welding and cutting metal later became common . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is more soluble in water than nitrogen is . <\s>
<s> Water in equilibrium with air contains approximately 1 molecule of dissolved O2 for every 2 molecules of N2 , compared to an atmospheric ratio of approximately 1 : 4 . <\s>
<s> The solubility of oxygen in water is temperature-dependent , and about twice as much dissolves at 0 °C than at 20 °C . <\s>
<s> At 25 °C and 1 standard atmosphere of air , freshwater contains about 6.04 milliliters of oxygen per liter , whereas seawater contains about 4.95 mL per liter . <\s>
<s> At 5 °C the solubility increases to 9.0 mL per liter for water and 7.2 mL per liter for sea water . <\s>
<s> Oxygen is the most abundant chemical element by mass in the Earth 's biosphere , air , sea and land . <\s>
