<s> Economist Simon Kuznets argued that levels of economic inequality are in large part the result of stages of development . <\s>
<s> According to Kuznets , countries with low levels of development have relatively equal distributions of wealth . <\s>
<s> As a country develops , it acquires more capital , which leads to the owners of this capital having more wealth and income and introducing inequality . <\s>
<s> Eventually , through various possible redistribution mechanisms such as social welfare programs , more developed countries move back to lower levels of inequality . <\s>
<s> Plotting the relationship between level of income and inequality , Kuznets saw middle-income developing economies level of inequality bulging out to form what is now known as the Kuznets curve . <\s>
<s> Kuznets demonstrated this relationship using cross-sectional data . <\s>
<s> However , more recent testing of this theory with superior panel data has shown it to be very weak . <\s>
<s> Kuznets ' curve predicts that income inequality will eventually decrease given time . <\s>
<s> As an example , income inequality did fall in the United States during its High school movement from 1910 to 1940 and thereafter . <\s>
<s> However , recent data shows that the level of income inequality began to rise after the 1970s . <\s>
<s> This does not necessarily disprove Kuznets ' theory . <\s>
<s> It may be possible that another Kuznets ' cycle is occurring , specifically the move from the manufacturing sector to the service sector . <\s>
<s> This implies that it may be possible for multiple Kuznets ' cycles to be in effect at any given time . <\s>
<s> Wealth concentration is a theoretical process by which , under certain conditions , newly created wealth concentrates in the possession of already-wealthy individuals or entities . <\s>
<s> According to this theory , those who already hold wealth have the means to invest in new sources of creating wealth or to otherwise leverage the accumulation of wealth , thus are the beneficiaries of the new wealth . <\s>
<s> Over time , wealth condensation can significantly contribute to the persistence of inequality within society . <\s>
<s> Thomas Piketty in his book Capital in the Twenty-First Century argues that the fundamental force for divergence is the usually greater return of capital than economic growth , and that larger fortunes generate higher returns . <\s>
<s> Economist Joseph Stiglitz argues that rather than explaining concentrations of wealth and income , market forces should serve as a brake on such concentration , which may better be explained by the non-market force known as `` rent-seeking '' . <\s>
<s> While the market will bid up compensation for rare and desired skills to reward wealth creation , greater productivity , etc. , it will also prevent successful entrepreneurs from earning excess profits by fostering competition to cut prices , profits and large compensation . <\s>
<s> A better explainer of growing inequality , according to Stiglitz , is the use of political power generated by wealth by certain groups to shape government policies financially beneficial to them . <\s>
<s> This process , known to economists as rent-seeking , brings income not from creation of wealth but from `` grabbing a larger share of the wealth that would otherwise have been produced without their effort '' <\s>
<s> Effects of inequality researchers have found include higher rates of health and social problems , and lower rates of social goods , a lower level of economic utility in society from resources devoted on high-end consumption , and even a lower level of economic growth when human capital is neglected for high-end consumption . <\s>
<s> For the top 21 industrialised countries , counting each person equally , life expectancy is lower in more unequal countries . <\s>
<s> A similar relationship exists among US states . <\s>
<s> 2013 Economics Nobel prize winner Robert J. Shiller said that rising inequality in the United States and elsewhere is the most important problem . <\s>
<s> Increasing inequality harms economic growth . <\s>
<s> High and persistent unemployment , in which inequality increases , has a negative effect on subsequent long-run economic growth . <\s>
<s> Unemployment can harm growth not only because it is a waste of resources , but also because it generates redistributive pressures and subsequent distortions , drives people to poverty , constrains liquidity limiting labor mobility , and erodes self-esteem promoting social dislocation , unrest and conflict . <\s>
<s> Policies aiming at controlling unemployment and in particular at reducing its inequality-associated effects support economic growth . <\s>
<s> British researchers Richard G. Wilkinson and Kate Pickett have found higher rates of health and social problems , and lower rates of social goods in countries and states with higher inequality . <\s>
<s> Using statistics from 23 developed countries and the 50 states of the US , they found social/health problems lower in countries like Japan and Finland and states like Utah and New Hampshire with high levels of equality , than in countries and states with large differences in household income . <\s>
<s> For most of human history higher material living standards – full stomachs , access to clean water and warmth from fuel – led to better health and longer lives . <\s>
<s> This pattern of higher incomes-longer lives still holds among poorer countries , where life expectancy increases rapidly as per capita income increases , but in recent decades it has slowed down among middle income countries and plateaued among the richest thirty or so countries in the world . <\s>
<s> Americans live no longer on average than Greeks or New Zealanders , though the USA has a higher GDP per capita . <\s>
<s> Life expectancy in Sweden and Japan – where income was more equally distributed – was longer . <\s>
<s> In recent years the characteristic that has strongly correlated with health in developed countries is income inequality . <\s>
<s> Creating an index of `` Health and Social Problems '' from nine factors , authors Richard Wilkinson and Kate Pickett found health and social problems `` more common in countries with bigger income inequalities '' , and more common among states in the US with larger income inequalities . <\s>
<s> Other studies have confirmed this relationship . <\s>
<s> The UNICEF index of `` child well-being in rich countries '' , studying 40 indicators in 22 countries , correlates with greater equality but not per capita income . <\s>
<s> Crime rate has also been shown to be correlated with inequality in society . <\s>
<s> Most studies looking into the relationship have concentrated on homicides – since homicides are almost identically defined across all nations and jurisdictions . <\s>
<s> There have been over fifty studies showing tendencies for violence to be more common in societies where income differences are larger . <\s>
<s> Research has been conducted comparing developed countries with undeveloped countries , as well as studying areas within countries . <\s>
<s> Daly et al. 2001 found that among U.S States and Canadian Provinces there is a tenfold difference in homicide rates related to inequality . <\s>
<s> They estimated that about half of all variation in homicide rates can be accounted for by differences in the amount of inequality in each province or state . <\s>
<s> Fajnzylber et al. found a similar relationship worldwide . <\s>
