<s> In addition to the Riemann hypothesis , many more conjectures revolving about primes have been posed . <\s>
<s> Often having an elementary formulation , many of these conjectures have withstood a proof for decades : all four of Landau 's problems from 1912 are still unsolved . <\s>
<s> One of them is Goldbach 's conjecture , which asserts that every even integer n greater than 2 can be written as a sum of two primes . <\s>
<s> As of February 2011 , this conjecture has been verified for all numbers up to n = 2 · 1017 . <\s>
<s> Weaker statements than this have been proven , for example Vinogradov 's theorem says that every sufficiently large odd integer can be written as a sum of three primes . <\s>
<s> Chen 's theorem says that every sufficiently large even number can be expressed as the sum of a prime and a semiprime , the product of two primes . <\s>
<s> Also , any even integer can be written as the sum of six primes . <\s>
<s> The branch of number theory studying such questions is called additive number theory . <\s>
<s> A third type of conjectures concerns aspects of the distribution of primes . <\s>
<s> It is conjectured that there are infinitely many twin primes , pairs of primes with difference 2 . <\s>
<s> Polignac 's conjecture is a strengthening of that conjecture , it states that for every positive integer n , there are infinitely many pairs of consecutive primes that differ by 2n . <\s>
<s> It is conjectured there are infinitely many primes of the form n2 + 1 . <\s>
<s> These conjectures are special cases of the broad Schinzel 's hypothesis H . <\s>
<s> Brocard 's conjecture says that there are always at least four primes between the squares of consecutive primes greater than 2 . <\s>
<s> Legendre 's conjecture states that there is a prime number between n2 and (n + 1)2 for every positive integer n . <\s>
<s> It is implied by the stronger Cramér 's conjecture . <\s>
<s> Giuga 's conjecture says that this equation is also a sufficient condition for p to be prime . <\s>
<s> Another consequence of Fermat 's little theorem is the following : if p is a prime number other than 2 and 5 , 1/p is always a recurring decimal , whose period is p − 1 or a divisor of p − 1 . <\s>
<s> The fraction 1/p expressed likewise in base q has similar effect , provided that p is not a prime factor of q . <\s>
<s> Wilson 's theorem says that an integer p > 1 is prime if and only if the factorial (p − 1)! + 1 is divisible by p . <\s>
<s> Moreover , an integer n > 4 is composite if and only if (n − 1)! is divisible by n . <\s>
<s> Several public-key cryptography algorithms , such as RSA and the Diffie–Hellman key exchange , are based on large prime numbers . <\s>
<s> RSA relies on the assumption that it is much easier to perform the multiplication of two numbers x and y than to calculate x and y if only the product xy is known . <\s>
<s> The Diffie–Hellman key exchange relies on the fact that there are efficient algorithms for modular exponentiation , while the reverse operation the discrete logarithm is thought to be a hard problem . <\s>
<s> The evolutionary strategy used by cicadas of the genus Magicicada make use of prime numbers . <\s>
<s> These insects spend most of their lives as grubs underground . <\s>
<s> They only pupate and then emerge from their burrows after 7 , 13 or 17 years , at which point they fly about , breed , and then die after a few weeks at most . <\s>
<s> The logic for this is believed to be that the prime number intervals between emergences make it very difficult for predators to evolve that could specialize as predators on Magicicadas . <\s>
<s> If Magicicadas appeared at a non-prime number intervals , say every 12 years , then predators appearing every 2 , 3 , 4 , 6 , or 12 years would be sure to meet them . <\s>
<s> Over a 200-year period , average predator populations during hypothetical outbreaks of 14- and 15-year cicadas would be up to 2 % higher than during outbreaks of 13- and 17-year cicadas . <\s>
<s> Though small , this advantage appears to have been enough to drive natural selection in favour of a prime-numbered life-cycle for these insects . <\s>
<s> The concept of prime number is so important that it has been generalized in different ways in various branches of mathematics . <\s>
<s> Generally , `` prime '' indicates minimality or indecomposability , in an appropriate sense . <\s>
<s> For example , the prime field is the smallest subfield of a field F containing both 0 and 1 . <\s>
<s> It is either Q or the finite field with p elements , whence the name . <\s>
<s> Often a second , additional meaning is intended by using the word prime , namely that any object can be , essentially uniquely , decomposed into its prime components . <\s>
<s> For example , in knot theory , a prime knot is a knot that is indecomposable in the sense that it can not be written as the knot sum of two nontrivial knots . <\s>
<s> Any knot can be uniquely expressed as a connected sum of prime knots . <\s>
<s> Prime models and prime 3-manifolds are other examples of this type . <\s>
<s> Prime numbers give rise to two more general concepts that apply to elements of any commutative ring R , an algebraic structure where addition , subtraction and multiplication are defined : prime elements and irreducible elements . <\s>
<s> An element p of R is called prime element if it is neither zero nor a unit and satisfies the following requirement : given x and y in R such that p divides the product xy , then p divides x or y . <\s>
<s> An element is irreducible if it is not a unit and can not be written as a product of two ring elements that are not units . <\s>
