<s> The French and Indian War was the North American theater of the worldwide Seven Years ' War . <\s>
<s> The war was fought between the colonies of British America and New France , with both sides supported by military units from their parent countries of Great Britain and France , as well as Native American allies . <\s>
<s> At the start of the war , the French North American colonies had a population of roughly 60,000 European settlers , compared with 2 million in the British North American colonies . <\s>
<s> The outnumbered French particularly depended on the Indians . <\s>
<s> Long in conflict , the metropole nations declared war on each other in 1756 , escalating the war from a regional affair into an intercontinental conflict . <\s>
<s> The war was fought primarily along the frontiers between New France and the British colonies , from Virginia in the South to Nova Scotia in the North . <\s>
<s> It began with a dispute over control of the confluence of the Allegheny and Monongahela rivers , called the Forks of the Ohio , and the site of the French Fort Duquesne and present-day Pittsburgh , Pennsylvania . <\s>
<s> The dispute erupted into violence in the Battle of Jumonville Glen in May 1754 , during which Virginia militiamen under the command of 22-year-old George Washington ambushed a French patrol . <\s>
<s> In 1755 , six colonial governors in North America met with General Edward Braddock , the newly arrived British Army commander , and planned a four-way attack on the French . <\s>
<s> None succeeded and the main effort by Braddock was a disaster ; he was defeated in the Battle of the Monongahela on July 9 , 1755 and died a few days later . <\s>
<s> British operations in 1755 , 1756 and 1757 in the frontier areas of Pennsylvania and New York all failed , due to a combination of poor management , internal divisions , and effective Canadian scouts , French regular forces , and Indian warrior allies . <\s>
<s> In 1755 , the British captured Fort Beauséjour on the border separating Nova Scotia from Acadia ; soon afterward they ordered the expulsion of the Acadians . <\s>
<s> Orders for the deportation were given by William Shirley , Commander-in-Chief , North America , without direction from Great Britain . <\s>
<s> The Acadians , both those captured in arms and those who had sworn the loyalty oath to His Britannic Majesty , were expelled . <\s>
<s> Native Americans were likewise driven off their land to make way for settlers from New England . <\s>
<s> After the disastrous 1757 British campaigns , the British government fell . <\s>
<s> William Pitt came to power and significantly increased British military resources in the colonies at a time when France was unwilling to risk large convoys to aid the limited forces it had in New France . <\s>
<s> France concentrated its forces against Prussia and its allies in the European theatre of the war . <\s>
<s> Between 1758 and 1760 , the British military launched a campaign to capture the Colony of Canada . <\s>
<s> They succeeded in capturing territory in surrounding colonies and ultimately Quebec . <\s>
<s> Though the British were later defeated at Sainte Foy in Quebec , the French ceded Canada in accordance with the 1763 treaty . <\s>
<s> The outcome was one of the most significant developments in a century of Anglo-French conflict . <\s>
<s> France ceded its territory east of the Mississippi to Great Britain . <\s>
<s> It ceded French Louisiana west of the Mississippi River to its ally Spain , in compensation for Spain 's loss to Britain of Florida . <\s>
<s> France 's colonial presence north of the Caribbean was reduced to the islands of Saint Pierre and Miquelon , confirming Britain 's position as the dominant colonial power in eastern North America . <\s>
<s> The conflict is known by multiple names . <\s>
<s> In British America , wars were often named after the sitting British monarch , such as King William 's War or Queen Anne 's War . <\s>
<s> As there had already been a King George 's War in the 1740s , British colonists named the second war in King George 's reign after their opponents , and it became known as the French and Indian War . <\s>
<s> This traditional name continues as the standard in the United States , but it obscures the fact that Indians fought on both sides of the conflict , and that this was part of the Seven Years ' War , a much larger conflict between France and Great Britain . <\s>
<s> American historians generally use the traditional name or sometimes the Seven Years ' War . <\s>
<s> Other , less frequently used names for the war include the Fourth Intercolonial War and the Great War for the Empire . <\s>
<s> In Europe , the North American theater of the Seven Years ' War usually is not given a separate name . <\s>
<s> The entire international conflict is known as the Seven Years ' War . <\s>
<s> `` Seven Years '' refers to events in Europe , from the official declaration of war in 1756 to the signing of the peace treaty in 1763 . <\s>
<s> These dates do not correspond with the fighting on mainland North America , where the fighting between the two colonial powers was largely concluded in six years , from the Battle of Jumonville Glen in 1754 to the capture of Montreal in 1760 . <\s>
<s> The French population numbered about 75,000 and was heavily concentrated along the St. Lawrence River valley , with some also in Acadia . <\s>
<s> Fewer lived in New Orleans , Biloxi , Mississippi , Mobile , Alabama and small settlements in the Illinois Country , hugging the east side of the Mississippi River and its tributaries . <\s>
<s> French fur traders and trappers traveled throughout the St. Lawrence and Mississippi watersheds , did business with local tribes , and often married Indian women . <\s>
<s> Traders married daughters of chiefs , creating high-ranking unions . <\s>
<s> British settlers outnumbered the French 20 to 1 with a population of about 1.5 million ranged along the eastern coast of the continent , from Nova Scotia and Newfoundland in the north , to Georgia in the south . <\s>
<s> Many of the older colonies had land claims that extended arbitrarily far to the west , as the extent of the continent was unknown at the time their provincial charters were granted . <\s>
<s> While their population centers were along the coast , the settlements were growing into the interior . <\s>
<s> Nova Scotia , which had been captured from France in 1713 , still had a significant French-speaking population . <\s>
<s> Britain also claimed Rupert 's Land , where the Hudson 's Bay Company traded for furs with local tribes . <\s>
<s> In between the French and the British , large areas were dominated by native tribes . <\s>
<s> To the north , the Mi ' kmaq and the Abenaki were engaged in Father Le Loutre 's War and still held sway in parts of Nova Scotia , Acadia , and the eastern portions of the province of Canada , as well as much of present-day Maine . <\s>
<s> The Iroquois Confederation dominated much of present-day Upstate New York and the Ohio Country , although the latter also included Algonquian-speaking populations of Delaware and Shawnee , as well as Iroquoian-speaking Mingo . <\s>
<s> These tribes were formally under Iroquois rule , and were limited by them in authority to make agreements . <\s>
<s> Further south the Southeast interior was dominated by Siouan-speaking Catawba , Muskogee-speaking Creek and Choctaw , and the Iroquoian-speaking Cherokee tribes . <\s>
<s> When war broke out , the French used their trading connections to recruit fighters from tribes in western portions of the Great Lakes region , including the Huron , Mississauga , Ojibwa , Winnebago , and Potawatomi . <\s>
<s> The British were supported in the war by the Iroquois Six Nations , and also by the Cherokee – until differences sparked the Anglo-Cherokee War in 1758 . <\s>
<s> In 1758 the Pennsylvania government successfully negotiated the Treaty of Easton , in which a number of tribes in the Ohio Country promised neutrality in exchange for land concessions and other considerations . <\s>
<s> Most of the other northern tribes sided with the French , their primary trading partner and supplier of arms . <\s>
<s> The Creek and Cherokee were subject to diplomatic efforts by both the French and British to gain either their support or neutrality in the conflict . <\s>
<s> It was not uncommon for small bands to participate on the `` other side '' of the conflict from formally negotiated agreements , as most tribes were decentralized and bands made their own decisions about warfare . <\s>
<s> At the start of the war , no French regular army troops were stationed in North America , and few British troops . <\s>
<s> New France was defended by about 3,000 troupes de la marine , companies of colonial regulars . <\s>
<s> The colonial government recruited militia support when needed . <\s>
<s> Most British colonies mustered local militia companies , generally ill trained and available only for short periods , to deal with native threats , but did not have any standing forces . <\s>
<s> Céloron 's expedition force consisted of about 200 Troupes de la marine and 30 Indians . <\s>
<s> The expedition covered about 3,000 miles between June and November 1749 . <\s>
<s> It went up the St. Lawrence , continued along the northern shore of Lake Ontario , crossed the portage at Niagara , and followed the southern shore of Lake Erie . <\s>
<s> At the Chautauqua Portage , the expedition moved inland to the Allegheny River , which it followed to the site of present-day Pittsburgh . <\s>
<s> There Céloron buried lead plates engraved with the French claim to the Ohio Country . <\s>
<s> Whenever he encountered British merchants or fur-traders , Céloron informed them of the French claims on the territory and told them to leave . <\s>
<s> When Céloron 's expedition arrived at Logstown , the Native Americans in the area informed Céloron that they owned the Ohio Country and that they would trade with the British regardless of the French . <\s>
<s> Céloron continued south until his expedition reached the confluence of the Ohio and the Miami rivers , which lay just south of the village of Pickawillany , the home of the Miami chief known as `` Old Briton '' . <\s>
<s> Céloron threatened `` Old Briton '' with severe consequences if he continued to trade with the British . <\s>
<s> `` Old Briton '' ignored the warning . <\s>
<s> Disappointed , Céloron returned to Montreal in November 1749 . <\s>
<s> In his extensively detailed report , Céloron wrote , All I can say is that the Natives of these localities are very badly disposed towards the French , and are entirely devoted to the English . <\s>
<s> I do n't know in what way they could be brought back . <\s>
<s> Even before his return to Montreal , reports on the situation in the Ohio Country were making their way to London and Paris , each side proposing that action be taken . <\s>
<s> William Shirley , the expansionist governor of the Province of Massachusetts Bay , was particularly forceful , stating that British colonists would not be safe as long as the French were present . <\s>
<s> Conflicts between the colonies , accomplished through raiding parties that included Indian allies , had taken place for decades , leading to a brisk trade in European colonial captives from either side . <\s>
<s> In 1749 the British government gave land to the Ohio Company of Virginia for the purpose of developing trade and settlements in the Ohio Country . <\s>
<s> The grant required that it settle 100 families in the territory , and construct a fort for their protection . <\s>
<s> But , as the territory was also claimed by Pennsylvania , both colonies began pushing for action to improve their respective claims . <\s>
<s> In 1750 Christopher Gist , acting on behalf of both Virginia and the company , explored the Ohio territory and opened negotiations with the Indian tribes at Logstown . <\s>
<s> He completed the 1752 Treaty of Logstown in which the local Indians , through their `` Half-King '' Tanacharison and an Iroquois representative , agreed to terms that included permission to build a `` strong house '' at the mouth of the Monongahela River . <\s>
<s> By the late 17th century , the Iroquois had pushed many tribes out of the Ohio Valley , and kept it as hunting ground by right of conquest . <\s>
<s> The War of the Austrian Succession formally ended in 1748 with the signing of the Treaty of Aix-la-Chapelle . <\s>
